abstract: PARIS, March 2.--The Memorial Diplomatique corroborates the report that England has suggested to Russia that the Porte be allowed a respite to carry into effect the promised reforms. So far the pourparlers on this proposition have been fruitless, becuase Russia insists that England shall enter into some engagement respecting the course to be followed at a future date, an undertaking which England declines to give.

abstract: The newly-built frigate Trenton, which bad been in sailing condition for several days previous, was peremptorily ordered to sea yesterday afternoon. abstract: There are no particularly new features of interest relating to market supplies. Everything of an edible character is plentiful, and prices are generally low. Fish and eggs are abundant. Batter is plentiful, and the rates for it are gradually falling to the standard which prevailed before the war.

abstract: The Rochester Union says that Mr. A. B. Lumberton, of that city, has kept a record of the arrival of birds for some years past. In 1872 the first robins were observed there March 28. Wild geese were going north March 29, and snipe were found April 17. That was a backward year. In 1873 robins came March 13, sparrows 17th, blue birds 18th, pigeons 19th, Snipe and woodcock were found at Victor March 28.

abstract: A white walker in the South is as rare as a white crow. I have not seen' a white man wall half a mile since I left New-York. So the foot-path has a sombre sentiment as the track of a down trodden race through fields of labor and secretive woods and cane-brakes. While following its short-cut through a swamp or a pine grove I sometimes met a negro hurrying to town.

abstract: The British House of Commons is now for the first time in many years complete. The election of the Solicitor-General, who was returned from Launceston the 3d inst., once more makes the membership number no loss than 652, or the same as on March 5, 1874 the date on which the writs for the present Parliament were made returnable. Six seats, however, are vacant, and have been so since 1870.

abstract: WASHINGTON, March 26.--Secretaries Schurz and Evarts are still engaged upon the civil service rules, and expect to have them completed, and, if approved, in operation by the 1st of April. Their work upon this subject is expected to result in a few practical rules which will be so elastic as to be applicable to all the departments.

abstract: LONG BRANCH, March 26.--A fearful storm has been raging along the Jersey coast for the last 40 hours, sweeping almost everything before it. This evening the steamer Rusland was only a few feet out of water, and was continually being lost from view by immense waves and breakers, covering as high as her smoke-stack. She lies almost parallel with the shore, and seems to be fast in the sand.
